rankings.title: Does Losing Parental Health Insurance at Age 26 Shift Births to Medicaid? (RDD)
rankings.strengths: High policy salience (Medicaid vs private payment at delivery) and extremely large natality microdata gives strong precision. The age-26 cutoff is plausibly exogenous and directly tied to the insurance mechanism you measure (payer at delivery).
rankings.concerns: In the public-use Natality file, mother's age is typically measured in integer years, not exact days-from-birthdayâ€”so this is not a truly sharp birthday RDD; it's effectively a discrete/fuzzy RD with substantial treatment misclassification.

rankings.title: Did Removing Age Restrictions on Emergency Contraception Reduce Teen Pregnancy? (RDD-in-time)
rankings.strengths: The policy date is clear and national, and teen birth outcomes are measurable at high frequency with CDC data.
rankings.concerns: RD-in-time is fragile here: teen birth rates were already on a strong secular downward trend.

rankings.title: Did OTC Birth Control (Opill) Approval Affect Fertility? (RDD-in-time)
rankings.strengths: Very high policy relevance and potentially high upside.
rankings.concerns: No sharp threshold and the post-period is heavily confounded.

rankings.title: Does Age 18 Eligibility for Pharmacist-Prescribed Contraception Increase Use? (Age-18 RDD)
rankings.strengths: The policy margin (pharmacist prescribing) is concrete and potentially important for access.
rankings.concerns: The age-18 cutoff is a confounding magnet.

summary: One genuinely fundable idea: the age-26 dependent coverage project.
